## PART 2 \'97 "BOUGHT AT THE TOP" FULL HTML PIECE (REFERENCE SPEC \'97 ONLY USED ON "UPDATE")\
\
Everything below describes how to regenerate the HTML from scratch. This is only needed when the user says "update" and the underlying data has changed. For normal requests, just serve the pre-built file per the routing logic above.\
\
### \uc0\u9889  CRITICAL: TEMPLATE ARCHITECTURE\
\
The HTML file is a **self-contained template** that computes all dollar values client-side from embedded JSON factors. This means:\
\
1. **The factors JSON blob is embedded directly inside the HTML** in a `<script>` tag\
2. **JavaScript computes every dollar value** from `investment \'d7 factor` \'97 no dollar amounts are hardcoded in the HTML\
3. **An interactive input** lets users change the investment amount in the browser \'97 all values update live\
4. **All static content** (narratives, pain boxes, methodology text, crash descriptions) is written directly in the HTML\
5. **Placeholder `<span>` elements** with data attributes or IDs are populated by JS on page load and on input change\
\
### What this means for generation\
\
| Situation | What to do |\
|-----------|------------|\
| User asks for the piece at ANY dollar amount | Read `cached_factors.json`, embed it as JSON in the template, set the default `investment` variable to the requested amount. Generate one HTML file. |\
| User changes the amount later | Just tell them to use the input in the browser \'97 OR re-serve the same file (it already handles any amount). No regeneration needed. |\
| User says "update" | Re-run Python for all 8 scenarios, overwrite `cached_factors.json`, regenerate the HTML with the new JSON blob. |\
| User asks to tweak design/text | Edit the HTML template. The data layer (JSON + JS) stays the same. |\
\
### HTML template structure\
\
The template has three layers:\
\
**Layer 1 \'97 Embedded data (JSON)**\
```html\
<script>\
const FACTORS = \{/* entire cached_factors.json contents */\};\
let investment = 1000000; // default, overridden by input\
</script>\
```\
\
**Layer 2 \'97 Static content (HTML)**\
All narratives, pain boxes, methodology text, section headings, and structure are written directly in the HTML. These never change when the amount changes.\
\
**Layer 3 \'97 Dynamic values (JS)**\
A `render()` function computes and injects all dollar values:\
```javascript\
function render() \{\
  FACTORS.scenarios.forEach(s => \{\
    const scaled = investment * (s.cpi_start / FACTORS.cpi_end);\
    const realEnd = scaled * s.real_tr_f;\
    const nomEnd = scaled * s.nom_tr_f;\
    const priceOnly = scaled * s.price_r_f;\
    // ... inject into DOM via data-scenario attributes\
  \});\
\}\
```\
\
Dollar formatting helper:\
```javascript\
function fmt(n) \{\
  if (n >= 1e6) return '$' + (n/1e6).toFixed(1) + 'M';\
  if (n >= 1e3) return '$' + Math.round(n).toLocaleString();\
  return '$' + n.toFixed(0);\
\}\
```\
\
### DOM binding pattern\
\
Use `data-scenario="N"` and `data-field="fieldname"` attributes on spans:\
```html\
<span data-scenario="1" data-field="invested"></span>\
<span data-scenario="1" data-field="real_end"></span>\
```\
\
The `render()` function queries all `[data-scenario]` spans and fills them. This keeps the HTML readable and the data injection centralized.\
\
For global values (hero subtitle, methodology box), use class-based selectors:\
```html\
<span class="inv-ref"></span>  <!-- shows formatted investment amount everywhere -->\
```\
