### The CPI scaling concept\
\
The key insight: rather than showing a flat $100,000 at each peak (which would make 1929 look artificially huge), scale each investment using CPI so every scenario represents the same real purchasing power as $100,000 today.\
\
Formula: `historical_amount = $100,000 \'d7 (CPI_at_peak \'f7 CPI_at_end_of_dataset)`\
\
This is handled automatically by the `analyze()` function above \'97 the `scaled` field IS the CPI-adjusted investment. In the template, JS computes this live: `investment * (s.cpi_start / FACTORS.cpi_end)`.\
\
### Crash narratives (use these exact texts)\
\
**Sep 1929:** "The market will never recover." The Dow didn't reclaim its 1929 high until 1954 \'97 25 years later. And yet, with dividends reinvested, the patient investor went on to extraordinary wealth.\
*Pain:* Market fell 89% peak-to-trough. By 1932, the investment had shrunk to ~20\'a2 on the dollar. Most investors sold in panic and locked in permanent losses.\
\
**Feb 1937:** Markets had recovered 80% from the Depression lows by 1937 \'97 then the Fed tightened prematurely, sending stocks down another 60%. Investors who'd just returned were crushed again.\
*Pain:* Two consecutive crashes within a decade. It took until 1945 to break even on price alone.\
\
**Nov 1968:** The "Nifty Fifty" era \'97 glamour stocks at any price. Then oil shocks, Vietnam, Nixon's resignation, and 15% inflation. The 1970s were the worst decade for real returns in market history.\
*Pain:* Real inflation-adjusted losses persisted for over a decade. By 1982, purchasing power was still negative vs. the 1968 entry. A brutal 14-year grind.\
\
**Jan 1973:** OPEC's oil embargo sent inflation to 12%, stocks crashed 48%, and the U.S. entered its worst recession since the Depression. The Nifty Fifty darlings lost 80\'9690% individually.\
\
**Aug 1987:** On October 19, 1987, the Dow fell 22.6% in a single day \'97 the largest one-day drop in history. The market had been "too high" for months. It fully recovered within 2 years.\
*(No pain box for this one \'97 recovery was too fast.)*\
